ou look at my reviews you will see I am not someone who gives two giggles about graphics.  I play some very stripped down games, and it makes no matter to me.  What does frustrate me here is all the buildings are so samey and iconless, that the graphics (which take up most of the screen obviously) are just conveying very little information.  The buildings are not super distinguishable, the landforms and status effects on land not so either.  It just all looks kind of muddy, and unhelpful.  It doesn't need to be some colorful, cartoonish, finger painting.  But it does not \"spark joy\".\n\nI also find myself fighting with the interface a bit more than I would like in  game like this, and just find reading information off the map, or identifying trouble spots more annoying that I would like.  Want to remediate soil?  Lets click on each and every building and try and figure out where that is needed.  Want to upgrade a type of building, have fun scanning a hundred buildings trying to find each one of that type.\n\nI feel like the development direction, rather than honing what was already a great game, has focused on making the game more busy.  Adding more things.  Meteors, temples, whatever.  What the game really needed was to hone and refine its core mechanics/presentation, not add more bells and whistles.\n\nI guess for me this game sits kind of uncomfortably in this valley, where it just isn't quite interesting and engaging enough to be a meaty replayable strategy juggernaut, but isn't light and enjoyable enough to be a \"semi-causal\" art piece.  Just to be clear I don't like causal games at all, and almost never play them.  So I am not looking for that.  But there are the types of games you pour 20 hours into over and over again, and the type you dabble around with for a week or two because they are pleasing.  And I just feel like this currently sits somewhere in the uncomfortable middle.\n\nOverall this review is getting too negative, there is a lot to like here. 