tive. it's essentially an RTS with maps that loop around the x axis. small planets. land is at a premium. while u can just clear cut and build, u quickly realize u're wasting resources. \n\nthe game is full of these tense choices. at first I just played around. now before every map I pause, take stock of everything. where will I land? and once there, what do I choose to license? how do I make the most of my landing zone? this game is a real time strategy game, yes, but it's a war of economies more than destroying ur enemy with violent force. \n\nit's casual in the sense that the game employs automation to reduce gamer fatigue. I'm kept busy enough to pause the game (during which u can still interact with the game world and issue build commands, provided u have the capital), so it keeps u busy. but every move feels that much more significant overall. the gameplay rewards careful planning and execution. \n\nthere's a challenging and meaningful campaign. meaningful in that, they introduce the various sides and breathe life into them. a lot of these kinda games suffer from a soulless problem. not here tho. I feel I'm a part of a living world, not just a numbers simulator. in fact it will challenge ur morals. will u pollute and pay to cleanup making ur populace sick and annoyed or will u run clean and lean? the simulation includes global warming as an ultimate end game test. another way to bring more depth to the experience.", "timestamp_created": 1560110031, "timestamp_updated": 1560110031, "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 14, "votes_funny": 0, "weighted_vote_score": "0.584725558757781982", "comment_count": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "received_for_free": false, "written_during_early_access": true}, "51139874": {"recommendationid": "51139874", "author": {"steamid": "76561198097719319", "num_games_owned": 149, "num_reviews": 3, "playtime_forever": 1185, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "playtime_at_review": 835, "last_played": 1560610328}, "language": "english", "review": "I've