ll the bulidings right away, and buildings you place can only be upgraded if you enable their upgrades in a sort of upgrade skill tree (they play to change this). Most buildings have a resource requirement (producing MUCH less if they aren't placed on a given resource) and/or a bonus for being placed next to certain buildings/land features, meaning that you have to tailor your initial unlocks to the landscape of your starting environment. Later unlocks will probably coincide with the resources around your additional colonies, but can also be used for utility bulidings that help keep your economy running. The strategy and choice involved keep the gameplay varied so that even campaign missions with pre-generated maps can be played in many differnet ways.\n\nI can't speak much about the early access development cycle as all of my playtime was in a single patch over the course of a week while waiting for Monster Hunter to come out. That being said, when I ran into a game-stopping bug at one point and reported it to the developers, they had it fixed by the next morning. I appreciate the heck out of that. The developers are also very responsive to less-extreme bug reports and appreciate feedback.\n\nRegardless of the development cycle, the gameplay in its current state feels and plays like a complete game. I've pretty much only played the campaign missions, but those alone are worth the $20 price tag for any fan of city-bulider games. \n\nSome balance/polish improvements would help the game feel less early-access like for sure, but it feels like I'm nit-picking a $40 game at that point. If I have to treat a $20 game like a $40 game for its flaws to stand out, that's probably a good sign.", "timestamp_created": 1533650026, "timestamp_updated": 1538069641, "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 21, "votes_funny": 0, "weighted_vote_score": "0.664706885814666748", "comment_count": 4, "steam_purchase": true, "received_for_free": false, "written_during_early_access": true}, "43961015": 