ollution. Overproduction of energy, food and goods can be sold. There is also a science tree where you have to choose what you want to build or upgrade.\nThey also added enemy factions which you have to deal with, additionally to environmental hazards. It really is difficult to maintain a healthy environment when you have to compete against an opponent.\n\nBefore concluding, I will list some pros and cons about the game.\n\nPro:\n[list]\n    [*] Very good core gameplay.\n    [*] Different game modes and a campaign (Which is very good for the current state).\n    [*] A simple but good economics system. Not too complex but not too simple either.\n    [*] A high replay value, since you can try the same scenarios with different strategies even though you have to adapt to    the environment.\n    [*] Constantly Updated.\n[/list]\n\nContra:\n[list]\n    [*] Don\u2019t expect too much from the graphic effects, here is a lot room for improvement.\n    [*] The presentation of the campaign is boring (typical text boxes) which is a pity since the mission design itself is well done.\n    [*] The music is nothing special (However, this a problem most games in the genre have).\n[/list]\n\nNeutral: \n[list]\n    [*] The controls are ok. Though, they could improve some minor things like the navigation on the Planet. E.g. zooming in where my cursor is not the camera center.\n    [*] Some people complain about the User Interface, I think it is ok though. Again, it is certainly not the best I have seen but it does its job and didn\u2019t have problems with it.\n[/list]\n\nRegarding the graphics, effects, 3D models and textures aside. I think the best improvement would be to add more animations. I have to compare to Anno2070 here, since what made the graphics so nice were the many details, the moving parts of the factories or the farming robots and the flying cars in the city. You always had stuff to look at. Maybe working with such things is a better improvement than cranking up the t