on that colonizes distant planets for big profits. The game comes with a nice campaign, introducing you to likeable characters that guide you through your first steps. Expect to fail in the second mission anyways. Even though the tutorial is very well designed and gives a good guidance, the game itself remains a challenge.\nYou start of every new colony by placing your first town centre on the planet. Soon enough new colonists will move in and develop a demand for food, energy and goods. \nBy the games triangular grid, every building has - yes, that's right - three sides. And as you place buildings next to each other they possibly gain benefits or detriments from each other. So in this way Imagine Earth actually resembles \"Reus\". For example, you can increase the energy output of biomass plants by placing them next to forests or farms. But your inhabitants will become unhappy if you build coal plants next to their houses. Since building space is limited, conflicts are inevitable and part of the challenge arises from the task to place your buildings in the most productive and proficient way. \n[b]What's else:[/b] On the other hand there are different types or tiles of terrain. So you want to place your farms on fertile land or your gas plants on top of gas resources to maximize outcomes. This task gets significant harder by the fact that all your buildings create pollution, eventually triggering a greenhouse effect on your planet. Fertile land turns into desert, tornados and volcanoes arise and ultimatly your facing meltdown of the polar caps, rising global water level. To cut a long story short, [i]if you don't take care of your planet, it will want to get rid of you.[/i]\n[/b]]The graphics[/b] are a bit toony, which I personally enjoy very much. The planets themself looking like beautiful blue marbles that I - personally - feel a bit sad for, if my false management destroys them.\n[b]The Music[/b] itself is not extraordinarily remarkable but fits the pace of the game very good. (The speed of the music actually changes with the set game speed - mindblown!)\n[b]The story[/b] is also not quite thrilling but gives enough motivation to play through the campaign which I perceived mostly as a tutorial introducing my to new elements. Once your done with the rather short campaign, there is sandbox mode, challenge mode and a free play mode. You can play on planets, that are procedural created according to player set parameters - for instance like in [i]Tropico[/i] where you can choose size of the map, the amount of resources, etc... - what makes the game[b] a good value[/b]. \n(It seems that there is the idea of exchanging planets with your friends, competing for highscorse, but I can not confirm this.)\n[b]The controls[/b] are very simple and easy to pick up right away. One click opens the menu, one click lets you choose, one click places the building. \n\n[b]Flaws:[/b] As much as I enjoy Imagine Earth, there are two downsides. Even though the planets look beautiful, they feel a bit sterile, as streets stay empty, for example. Where are your 1.5 billion inhabitants? Building big cities is fun and the realy look cool as large skyscrapers emerge, but there is now life in the game. There are neither people or cars (like in Anno, where you get the impression of a busy citylife), nor animals roaming on the map.\nThe other minor flaw is, that you cant buy 5 buildings in a row, as you have to open the menu, select the building and place it for every building. Which I find a little unpractical and thus ironic in a game, that focus on maximizing efficiency.\n\n[b]Sum of us:[/b] This game is what I expected when I first got my hands on \"Reus\". If you were, like me, disappointed by Reus - even though solely based on your own false expectations - then this game is for you. If you like building simulations and management games, this game also is for you. If you are still sceptical, the [b]free demo[/b] is for you.\n\nImagine Earth is charming, challenging, a good value and a game of plain fun.\n", "timestamp_created": 1445885153, "timestamp_updated": 1445885153, "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 63, "votes_funny": 2, "weighted_vote_score": "0.761744201183319092", "comment_count": 1, "steam_purchase": true, "received_for_free": false, "written_during_early_access": true}, "18627942": {"recommendationid": "18627942", "author": {"steamid": "76561197991560209", "num_games_owned": 442, "num_reviews": 27, "playtime_forever": 106, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "playtime_at_review": 106, "last_played": 1441322455}, "language": "english", "review": "This game I found a little bit meh, I was expecting a lot more from it. I would give this an average score.", "timestamp_created": 1445533997, "timestamp_updated": 1445533997, "voted_up": false, "votes_up": 7, "votes_funny": 0, "weighted_vote_score": "0.454670369625091553", "comment_count": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "received_for_free": false, "written_during_early_access": true}, "18426011": {"recommendationid": "18426011", "author": {"steamid": "76561198205152977", "num_games_owned": 43, "num_reviews": 13, "playtime_forever": 10448, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "playtime_at_review": 2303, "last_played": 1613167242}, "language": "english", "review": "Nice charming game with lovely graphic, idea of global mechanic is very cool... And devs still releasing contest and polishing the game, sou i could only suggest it :)\n\nplus: - easy but addictive gameplay\n        - graphic reminds me something between old settlers and polulous but in new coat", "timestamp_created": 1444561128, "timestamp_updated": 1445592271, "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 15, "votes_funny": 0, "weighted_vote_score": "0.566642940044403076", "comment_count": 0, "steam_purchase": true, "received_for_free": false, "written_during_early_access": true}, "18405211": {"recommendationid": "18405211", "author": {"steamid": "76561198086749437", "num_games_owned": 148, "num_reviews": 19, "playtime_forever": 248, "p